ENHANCING PERFORMANCE OF YOUR BRIDGEBOARD


ADDBUFFERS - PC USING AMIGA's HARD DRIVE

	If the PC is using a fake C: drive or a JLINK drive, you can speed
	it up greatly by using the AmigaDOS ADDBUFFERS command.  For
	instance, if your fake C: drive resides on the Work: partition of
	your Amiga's hard drive, use the command

		ADDBUFFERS WORK: n

	where n is the size of the fake C: drive in megabytes times 20.
	For instance, if you have a 20 megabyte fake C: drive, you would
	use

		ADDBUFFERS WORK: 400

	which would use up 200K of your Amiga's memory.  Each buffer
	takes up 512 bytes (1/2K) of memory.


ADDBUFFERS - AMIGA USING PC'S HARD DRIVE

	If the Amiga is using the PC's hard drive (via DJMount) you can
	speed up the Amiga's access using the same method as outlined
	above.  Instead, add buffers to the JHx: volumes.


MS-DOS EQUIVALENTS TO ADDBUFFERS

	Disk caching programs (such as Microsoft's SMARTDRV.SYS) can be
	used to speed up the PC's access to fake C: drives as well as
	real PC hard drives.


A2386SX "SHADOW JANUS"

	If you have an A2386SX Bridgeboard, you should turn on the "SHADOW
	JANUS" switch in PCPrefs.  This will allow the 80386SX CPU to access
	the Janus Handler up to 5 times faster.  "SHADOW JANUS ON" will only
	work if you have enabled shadowing on the A2386SX BIOS Setup screen.

USING THE AMIGA-SIDE JANUS SOFTWARE

PCPREFS

	PCPrefs allows you to change various Bridgeboard operating
	parameters.  PCPrefs does not apply to the Sidecar, since
	the Sidecar is configured by DIP switches on it's motherboard.

	To run PCPrefs from workbench:

		Double click on the PCPrefs icon in the PC drawer.

	To run PCPrefs from CLI or Shell:

		Type "sys:pc/pcprefs".

	The following settings apply to the A2088, A2286, and A2386SX
	Bridgeboards:

	Janus Handler Load Segment: (2)
		This specifies the segment number in PC address space
		into which the Janus Handler BIOS extension will be
		loaded.  The following values are possible:

		Don't Load
			The Janus Handler is not loaded.  This setting
			should only be used if you do not intend to
			run any Janus software on the PC or Amiga.

		A000	The Janus Handler is loaded to segment A000.
			This setting should only be used if you do not
			intend to run any Janus software on the PC or
			Amiga, since the Bridgeboard's BIOS will not
			find BIOS extensions in segment A000.

		D000	The Janus Handler is loaded to segment D000.
			This setting is the default for the A2286 and
			A2386SX	Bridgeboards, and may also be used by the
			A2088 Bridgeboard.
	
		E000	The Janus Handler is loaded to segment E000.
			This setting is the default for the A2088
			Bridgeboard.  This setting does not apply to
			the A2286 or A2386SX.
	
	Monochrome Display Adapter Emulation: (3)
		This specifies whether the on-board MDA emulation hardware
		is enabled.

		Enabled	
			This is the normal setting.  The PC Mono program
			will display the screen of the emulated MDA card.

		Disabled
			If you have installed an MDA, Hercules, or VGA card
			in your system, you should select this setting to
			avoid addressing conflicts.

	Color Graphics Adapter Emulation: (3)
		This specifies whether the on-board CGA emulation hardware
		is enabled.

		Enabled	
			This is the normal setting.  The PC Color program
			will display the screen of the emulated CGA card.

		Disabled
			If you have installed any kind of color display
			card (CGA, EGA, VGA, etc) in your system, you
			should select this setting to avoid addressing
			conflicts.

	The following settings apply to the A2386SX Bridgeboard only:

	Janus Handler Shadowed: (2)
		This determines if the Janus Handler will shadow itself
		(copy itself from dual-port memory to high speed memory).

		Yes	Janus Handler will shadow itself if the BIOS
			Setup allows shadowing.  This setting causes
			Janus Handler to take up 16K of buffer memory.

		No	Janus Handler will not shadow itself.  This setting
			causes Janus Handler to take up 12K of buffer
			memory.

	Default Bridgeboard Video Mode: (3)
		This specifies what video mode the Bridgeboard BIOS starts
		up in.

		Monochrome
			The BIOS will attempt to use a monochrome display
			adapter (either the emulated MDA, or a card you
			have plugged into the PC/AT bus).

		Color
			The BIOS will attempt to use a color display
			adapter (either the emulated CGA, or a card you
			have plugged into the PC/AT bus).

	Bridgeboard Speaker:
		This controls the speaker on the Bridgeboard.

		On	The speaker will be audible.

		Off	The speaker will not be audible.

	Drive A: (3)
	Drive B: (3)
		These control the Flipper floppy disk multiplexing
		hardware.  The PC will not be able to access floppy
		drives properly if these settings are not correct.

		Internal
			The drive is attached to the "internal" drive
			connector (and usually installed inside the
			Amiga's case).

		External
			The drive is an A1010, A1011, A1020, or compatible
			external Amiga drive attached to the Bridgeboard's
			rear external drive connector.  Only one drive may
			be marked "External" at a time.

		Shared
			The drive is attached to the "shared" drive
			connectors and installed in the Amiga's case.
			Only one drive may be marked "Shared" at a time.

	Shared Amiga Drive: (1)
		Tells Flipper which Amiga drive is being shared (only
		used if "Shared" is selected for either Drive A or B).
		Flipper will malfunction if this setting is not correct.

		DF0:	The Amiga's DF0: drive is being shared.

		DF1:	The Amiga's DF1: drive is being shared.

	Shared Amiga Drive Type:
		Tells Flipper what kind of Amiga drive is being shared
		(only used if "Shared" is selected for either Drive A
		or B).  Flipper will malfunction if this setting is
		not correct.

		Standard
			The shared drive is a standard 880K Amiga drive.
			The PC must use it as a 720K drive.

		Dual Speed
			The shared drive is an 880K/1.76M Amiga drive.
			The PC can use it as either a 720K or 1.4M drive.


	Change a setting by clicking in the box containing it's value.

