MAKEAB

	MakeAB is used to create fake PC hard drives which exist on
	an Amiga volume as a large file.  There can be only one MakeAB
	drive.  The MakeAB drive appears to the PC to be a normal
	hard drive - it must be partitioned (FDISK) and formatted
	(FORMAT) like any other PC hard drive.  The PC can boot from
	the MakeAB drive.

	COMMAND LINE

		MakeAB FILENAME/A

	The filename is the name of the file which will contain an image
	of the fake hard drive.

	MakeAB will prompt you for the following information:

		Enter number of Heads (1-16):

	Type the number of "heads" you want the fake drive to have.
	A typical value is 4.

		Enter number of Sectors/Track (1-64):

	Type the number of "sectors" you want each "track" of the fake
	drive to have.  A typical value is 17.

		Enter number of Cylinders (1-1024):

	Type the number of "cylinders" you want the fake drive to have.
	See the table below for typical values.

	MakeAB will then print the values back out for you to verify and
	print the capacity of the resulting fake drive (in bytes) and the
	actual size of the MakeAB file (in bytes).  You will then be asked:

		Enter Y to accept, N to quit:

	Type "Y" if you are satisfied with the numbers, otherwise type "N".

	If you entered "Y", MakeAB will print:

		Creating FILENAME

	MakeAB will now attempt to create the file.  This can take a long
	time, depending on the speed of your hard drive controller and the
	size of the file.

	If MakeAB completes without any error messages, it will store the
	name of the MakeAB file in SYS:PC/System/Aboot.ctrl.  This is
	where the Janus software finds the name of the fake drive at boot
	time.

	You should now reboot the PC side, and partition and format your
	new C: drive using FDISK and FORMAT.


			    TYPICAL VALUES FOR MAKEAB

		MEGABYTES   BLOCKS	HEADS  SECTORS	CYLINDERS
		    5 	     10200	  4	  17	   150
		   10	     20468	  4	  17	   301
		   15	     30668	  4	  17	   451
		   20	     40936	  4	  17	   602
		   25	     51136	  4	  17	   752
		   32	     65484	  4	  17	   963


	ERROR MESSAGES

Too many parameters.

	Only one parameter is allowed (the name of the file to create).

Required parameter missing.

	You did not supply any parameters.

Error creating file.
Error writing, file deleted.
Not enough space on disk for file.

	The file could not be created (write protected disk, disk full,
	etc.).

Couldn't create SYS:PC/System/Aboot.ctrl
Couldn't write SYS:PC/System/Aboot.ctrl

	The file "SYS:PC/System/Aboot.ctrl," which contains the name of
